    <h3>
     Basic notes
    </h3>
    <ul>
     <li>
      Images update every 30 seconds.
      <li>
       North is up, West is right.
       <li>
        White is hot. Warm items (horizon features, clouds, the camera support veins) will appear brighter than the sky. The image however is a differential compilation of the past 10 raw images. Therefore, the darkest part of the image is not the sky level but the locations where hot items were in the last 5 minutes. This can be useful in some cases to determine the direction and speed of clouds.
        <li>
         Histogram of the image is displayed vertically along the right hand side of the image.
         <li>
          Numbers at the top-left of the image are the UT time, the sky level, and the sky standard deviation respectively from top to bottom. Running plots of these numbers for the night appear below the sky image.
          <li>
           The overlaid grid represents zenith angles incremented every 15 degrees in altitude and 45 degrees in azimuth.
           <li>
            The portion of the sky that the 2.5m and 3.5m telescopes are pointing are also overlayed on the image. This is useful for comparison to cloud positions.
           </li>
          </li>
         </li>
        </li>
       </li>
      </li>
     </li>
    </ul>
